This is also the phenomenon behind a lot of the backmasking panic of the 90's. Parents didn't like rock or metal music and so were predisposed to hear all kinds of things when the music was played backwards. They would then write what they thought they heard, and put that text for people to read as it played backwards. and the text would prime people to hear what they were told to hear.  I realized what was happening when a friend had 3 "messages" that he displayed while a song played backward and i heared them all when he played the same song backward. I then grew skeptical and always questioned what people told me i should hear.

Yet another DIY experiment...

Play a complex sterophonic recording through good earphones, try to locate all the instruments in space in front of you, as accurately as you can.

Now take off the headphones, eyes closed. Have someone next to you click their fingers...
Above your head.
To the side, below.
Around your head everywhichway.

Amazingly, even 'only' that you're given two ears to sense with - you can locate the point of origin of your friend's clicks extreemly accurately, to the point of being able to grasp their hand without opening your eyes.

So we can "see" with our ears quite fully around our head in 3D - despite only having two, you'd think we should only be able to hear in a ring around our head.

There's a lot of brain processing going on with that sound behind your ears...

A DIY experiment i once tried with my younger brother one summer evening.

I was smoking a cigarette outside in the evening twilight, noticed the red tip preceeded my hand a bit. So I got him over and we played, I moved my hand in a circle in front of me, faster and faster until the red tip of the cigarette was at one side of the circle, my hand at the other...

"Guess where my hand is?..." I said, "...It's actually at the red dot!"

To prove it I moved my hand instead back and forth between us in the same way, untill my hand was at one end, the tip of the cigarette at the other.

I had him bring his hand closer to the outer end, the cig. tip pointed in to my palm for safety. At a certain point, he felt my 'ghost hand' brush against his touch along with the red tip of the cig., even as he "saw" my hand at the point close to me in the twilight.

I imagine this could be done with a dim red LED as well.

the author Robert Anton Wilson, as in the book Prometheus Rising, has quite a few DIY experiments. One I've tried is take an old newspaper or a book, have someone hold it too far away to read.
Bring it almost to the point of readability closer.
Then have the person holding it say the title.
Almost at once, you can see the lettering.
This 'popping into view' has to be viscerally experienced to understand its impact.

I'm doing a PhD in cognitive neuroscience. I study visual representation.

The idea that our brain is a prediction system is not new. Research on false memories and schemas shows that our expectations can impact how we remember something. For example, participants in an office doing some random task, but not paying attention to the office itself may vehemently argue recalling that there were books on the shelf even if there weren't.

Whenever people say "I know what i saw" or are so sure of some thing they remember, that's their brain predicting what they should have seen. Memories are not recalled, they are reconstructed.

Basically, the point is, your memories and perceptions are very fallible. We always see what we want to see and we always hear what we want to hear. This is why science relies so heavily on peer review

Everything in this video is regarding how the brain processes sensory input and sends it TO the conscious mind.  The mind and the brain are not the same thing.   The brains are like the CPUs that take the inputs from the hard drive, the internet, etc. and then processes it into the video we just watched, as well as taking the keyboard input, processing it and sending it out over the internet so you can see this comment.  But just like the computer is not the user, the brain is not the mind.

I find my brain predicts far more than i actually perceive.
For example, i didn't wear glasses till my late twenties. I probably needed glasses long before that. So i got used to "seeing" what i couldn't really see. My mind does not need the full sentence for my mind to read it, and it actually sometimes sees words that aren't there, if it expects them. I find this a problem when I get my vision tested for new glasses. My mind can guess with a high rate of accuracy what the letter is, so I'm getting the letters correct, even though it is blurry.

I find this true in conversations and written word. My unconscious biases will cause me to interpret something different than the initial intention. As a weird example, i was having a conversation with a friend and i heard twenty dollars. I can bet my life i heard twenty dollars. I immediately asked her to clarify. She said five dollars, and she is absolutely sure she said five. For some reason i thought twenty, and expected her to say twenty. And I'm so sure that is what I heard.

What I've learned is that, 1. what I hear isn't always what they said, and if it is, 2. it might not have been what they meant, or that 3. it was not what i understood. (hope that made sense)

Consider this about the predictive nature of consciousness. Our nerves must conduct signals along electrochemical pathways to the brain.
For sight, this includes the image being inverted on the retinas as we blink at random, sliced into cell-sized signals, passed through nerves to the opposite side of the brain from the back, and then processed according to the brain's timed cycles. Note the brain routinely "records over" over the eye blinks as if they didn't happen.
The brain must analyze the signals against an immense set of existing patterns using a system with more connections than there are particles in the universe. We then become partially aware of this analysis and consider how much we accept that. This all takes at least a significant fraction of a second at best. "By the time you see me, I'm gone."
By then, the external situation has changed. We are inescapably "behind the beat".
Think of all this the next time you are tailgating someone a fraction of a second behind them at 80 mph. "It's ok, I've NEVER been in a wreck."

When I, and I'm sure many others can agree, dream about people, the person might be your cousin and the face you "see" in the dream at first is interpreted as your cousins face, but after waking up you think back and realize it was actually the face of your best friend.
Without any visual input, being asleep, is that why faces, objects, sounds, seem to be amorphous or vague in dreams? And what sort of state is our brain in when our dreams are crystal clear and indistinguishable from real life?

Not all trans women get to live as women or be treated as one.

Only cognitively impenetrable trans women will ever know what it means to "live like a woman" and get treated as one.

Anybody who other people perceive as a cognitively impenetrable illusion of a female entity.

I have been slowly making my way through Crash Course Psychology--like, with an academic eye, taking notes--and they are sure to mention this concept a lot. Your perception is shaped by your perceptual set, and the most important part of your perceptual set is your expectations.

When you realize how much you participate in confirmation bias--and you do, and you have, because everyone has, because it's the nature of our brains--your whole world opens up. Ideas you once stoutly rejected become understandable and acceptible. You approach the world with curiosity rather than judgment. You get to accept things as they are, for once, finally--in part because you realize that there is something about everything that you don't know, and that it's perfectly okay to not know.

Life is a very long game of telephone with yourself. Your message can get so warped that you couldn't empathize with your own past self. So warped you can't empathize with your fellow humans, even if you all started from the same place.

My dad relies on me emotionally, sometimes too much and I have to check him, but usually a somewhat appropriate amount. Between me and my two older brothers, I'm the only one still capable of having a casual and comfortable conversation with him without any subtext. I recently moved out of his house into a place with me and two friends, which has not been easy for either of us. I'm a very inept adult in a multitude ways but have been working to change that.

But a big reason why I did decide to make this move is because I'm trans. He doesn't know this but has seen enough "off" things to have very overt suspicions. For years, I've buried and hid it cause I didn't expect him to be ok with it or still want me around. Based on what he's said when he saw those "off" things, I don't think he is ok with it, but he'd never throw me away. He'd just have a lot of trouble adjusting and it wouldn't make him happy. That's not good, but it is a lot better than being disowned.

My mother on the other hand might disown me. See, the place I moved into is hers. She doesn't live there, but she does own it. I know for a fact all of these topics overtly disgust her, which is not making it any easier. On top of all this, she plans on visiting occasionally and staying in our basement, which she's renovating into a personal guest room. I moved out to feel safer and yet I feel no safer. Now there's a genuine threat of homelessness because unlike my dad, my mother holds no love for lgbt+ people.

I don't exactly hold much love for my mom either, so it's not an issue emotionally, but it is one physically.

I’m gonna go in a mini rant:

This is interesting to me because I have something called social pragmatic communication disorder (as well as the occasional hallucination caused by ptsd). I don’t inherently understand social cues, or misinterpret them. I’m often missing the context of situations, which makes sense as to why I struggle so hard in any kind of interaction(especially legal jargon, which is intentionally hard for regular people)

I have difficulty making connections because to most people, all of these cues are often unspoken and coloured entirely by our experiences. So when I do or say something (that I think is a normal or correct response), it’s like that person predicting the coffee cup, but seeing a glass of water instead. It definitely throws people for a loop. Tho sometimes I do wonder how aware of it people are, because I also have a stutter and most people are shocked when I tell them, but can hear it afterward.

So yeah, this video is very interesting to me. It does feel like I’m going about, experiencing life in that two tone or altered audio. I have a book of experience that tells me that’s a horse and a woman, even if I still can’t really see it. But I just keep on keeping on because it’s the only way I know.

I’ll end with a quote from Komi Can’t Communicate “An important thing to remember is, just because a person has problems communicating, doesn’t mean that person doesn’t want to communicate with others.”

6:07 Hello Mr. “Muy Cansado” 😂

“Soy” is only a part the verb to be. It’s only used for identity: who you are? what is your nationality? what is your height? … anything that is your identity

But emotions or feelings are not identities. So we use instead “estoy” which is the other part of the verb to be used for states. Like brain states, emotional states, your location, anything about you but that can change.

So if you want to say “I am very tired” then you should say “Yo estoy muy cansado” which represent your emotional state of being currently very tired.

But if you say “Yo soy muy cansado” you are saying that you are name, or nicknamed, or you identify as “muy cansado”.

So now you know that verbs in English and Spanish are not 1-to-1 related. Often there are multiple Spanish verbs to represent different cases when 1 English verb can be used for all cases.

Optical and auditory illusions like this don't work on me the way they do to other people.
Like, yeah I knew about the same-color optical illusion and I knew about two-tone images altered from color images and even though I didn't recognize a single word from the audio clip ("the man" sounded something almost like "hello" but not really, and instead of "sign" I heard "time")

But my brain doesn't make predictions like that. For the same-color illusion, I can in fact see through them and other like them by relaxing and unfocusing my eyes and slowly taking in the visual stimulation.
For the two-tone image, I can in fact still see it just as I did before I saw the original, and in the same way, I can process the audio clip and hear it as I did before hearing the original. Knowing about it, I can choose to apply that information to the stimulation, and see it from a certain perspective, and thus change how it appears to me, or I can willfully reinterpret it as well.

Interestingly, there is another example like this. “The Fields of Athenry” from the film “Veronica Guerin” is a perfect example. It is a young Irish boy singing a folk song. It is nearly impossible for American English speakers to understand unless they already know the words. Listening to it at first, it’s almost like listening to English if you don’t speak much English. You can pick up a couple words here and there, but not everything. But once you know it, it’s impossible to unhear. I highly recommend going to watch it (I’ll try and link it in a comment), then going to read the songtext and watch it again. Your mind will be blow.

I couldn't see anything from that image other than taking it at face value: it's just random splotches. It's like those images where they ask you what do you see from it, and of course there are many interpretations. If I look longer at that image, my imagination starts to wander, and now I see an alien figure or maybe something more horrid: a bloody crime scene. 👽😳

>>> Update, after watching the video: <<<
It never occurred to me to visualize the image in two tone. I was mainly focused on the details, trying to make sense of it, that I still couldn't see the image you described until you pulled it away, making it smaller, which allowed me to see the image as a whole. Now that was intriguing.

Furthermore, I was sure the recording would be close to what I predicted, but it was something else entirely. I guess if we weren't told what it actually said, our brains would automatically fill in the holes, regardless if it was right or wrong.

This shows we rely on our own assumptions, so much so, that often it's difficult to visualize or hear something else unless we get another perspective. We predict (or imagine) what it could be versus what it is in actuality, and what we see or hear depends on what we previously inputted in our brains (our past experiences, things we learn or see everyday, etc).

In the end, to be more understanding, we should strive to be less judgmental and be more curious.

This is pretty obvious. If there's a bowl of pineapple on the counter, and you intend on eating it, your brain will make a prediction about what it tastes like. If that prediction is wrong, it leads you to dislike, or really enjoy that pineapple, depending on prior knowledge of the taste of pineapple. That combined with outside factors like how longs its been sitting there, where it comes from, etc. Is what determines taste, but your senses and thus consciousness have to predict what it might taste like based on prior experience. If you ate that pineapple and it tasted like strawberry, you'd be shocked! That's your brains way of telling you wait a second this IS NOT what I predicted...

I'd say it's less about predictions, more about layering memories. How would the brain "predict"? First, you receive input from the world, then your neurons capture that input, then you receive more input from the world that *triggers* your memory and contextualises the new input. The word "prediction" assumes we expect an outcome, but expectance only comes from memory. Our brain likely doesn't actively do anything to "predict". We are simply a product of our past inputs, any new input is filtered through all the previous ones, and your outputted behaviour is like a chemical reaction. It exists very much in the present. Or as present as can be felt.

E.g. realising the above helps you look at those grey squares in that checkered optical illusion and realise geometry is favoured more than color by your past experience (I'm using this terminology to avoid using the more personified "the brain"), and now you can choose to blur your vision, and specifically focus on comparing color, and ignoring geometry. Then you see those squares are the same color. You CAN control how you perceive things. You aren't entirely at the mercy of "your brain". Unless what you mean by "your brain" is simply the weight of your past experiences, and "your brain" simply records, or has been evolved through your genetic line, to record the most pertinent information. Here, geometry over color. This means, more profoundly, that "your brain" mimics the world, and so it is the world that has selected geometry to be more valuable than color. And this enacts itself through you, who is part of the world.

The point is: your brain is just a complex input output system. Saying it *does* anything, that it "processes" anything is incorrect. You ARE the limitation. You ARE the favouring of geometry over color. Your brain is not a seperate entity from your consciousness, some God-like intervention influencing you. Your brain IS you, and you ARE limited, by experience and evolution, and the world. That seems to me, to be a more pertinent observation on ourselves and consciousness.

But a stimulating video nevertheless :)

I think this general theory of mind had been hypothesized by Karl Popper already since way back but with a metaphysical twist. The general gist however is still consistent: the mind (or the brain, even) is an organ which produces an "expectation" of the world in such-and-such a way that it can function in the world; this "expectation-formation" is then tested against experience by our senses (the brain/mind "hypothesized" or "formed the expectation" that "this is a cup of coffee", which in fact is wordless and moreso assumes certain things already before we experience that it is in fact "coffee": the expectations that the cup won't leak, that it has a certain aroma, that the "substance" in the coffee will be mildly bitter and sometimes even bittersweet, that it's drinkable,...

All these expectations are then put to the test by our senses: first by the sight of the cup not actually leaking, then by the aroma we can smell, then the taste,... Since Popper has also argued that "confirmation" is actually impossible and based on a logical fallacy ("coffee is bitter", "this is a cup of coffee" -> "this cup is bitter"; the fallacy arises when you think that "this cup is bitter" somehow "confirms" both of those statements that are used to derive it: the fallacy of affirming the consequent---the cup might just have been a cup of bitter water dyed black).

"New information about the cup" is only really learned when our expectations are betrayed: if the cup of coffee is actually disgustingly sweet, if there was no aroma (or the aroma is putrid), if there was no cup there at all but it's just a hologram,... This is precisely because the "information" that was "confirmed" was already expected by us so there's nothing new that's really added. So the actual role of "experience produced by the senses" are actually to check our expectations*. Furthermore, our "expectations" are necessarily not unique to this single instance. The expectation that "this is a cup of coffee" actually assumes something not particular to this cup, because the very idea of "coffee" transcends this particular experience and this particular expectation regarding *this cup. So, when the mind/brain "expects" a particular experience to be the case, it has actually used an expectation not limited to this particular experience, but can be generalized to all other possible experiences of the "same type": more succinctly put, what we "feel" as "similar circumstances" are actually what the brain has already interpreted to be the "same" in the aspect that it expects.

The "expectations" produced by the brain/mind, by necessity, transcend any particular observation or experience at any particular point in time.

The "predictions" of the mind, strictly interpreted, in this video are simply the "expectation" applied to a "particular experience".

This also makes sense since, for example, within ADHD there's something called "object permanence." Basically, out of sight out of mind, literally speaking. So you could have your keys sitting behind your coffee mug on your desk, and a few minutes later when you're looking for them you forget they're there and look everywhere but your desk. If your brain is always making predictions, then with a condition like ADHD in which patients suffer from difficulty encoding memory, then it makes sense that such brains would make erroneous predictions about the world around them. Causing peculiar scenarios like looking all over your apartment for your keys that were literally right behind the coffee mug because subconsciously you didn't register that.

Spaniard here. Not a bad pronunciation. The accent is obviously there but not that bad. Just a couple of notes: the "h" in Spanish is always silent, it's nothing like the English "h", there's no sound for it. And "I am tired" is "(yo) estoy cansado" (as you may very well know, contrary to English, in Spanish the subject may or may not be there).

"To be" has two different meanings and in Spanish it's two different words/verbs: "ser" and "estar". So, you would use "ser" with things like "I'am tall", "it's late" (though "I am late" would need a different verb altogether) "that is red". It's kind of related to "how things are", while "estar" is more like "how things feel" if you will, so you would use it in "I'm tired", "he's occupied", "she is talking".

And, mind you, sometimes using one or the other would completely change the meaning. Your sentence "soy cansado" is something you actually don't want to say. I think most people would actually understand you and thin you mean "I'm tired", "estoy cansado", but if you want to be precise in the translation, you would be actually saying "I'm tiresome", which is not what you mean at all.

The classic example is with "boring" and "bored". In Spanish both words are translated equal: "aburrido", and instead the different meaning comes from the verb that goes with it. So, you have "ser aburrido" and "estar aburrido", which are respectively "being boring" and "being bored". Therefore if you say you ared bored because you've been waiting for too long or whatever, you want to say "estoy aburrido". If you say "soy aburrido", you're saying it's you who's boring.

About the Spanish aspect of this video, two things.
I can tell from experience that knowledge of a sentence clarifies immensely the understanding of what's heard. Many times I don't understand a thing of what a song in English says, then I find the lyrics, and magically I understand everything.
The other thing, regarding you learning Spanish, first, congratulations. Second, watching TV or videos with subtitles in the same language helps a lot to get the meanings; I suppose it will be easier in Spanish, as the writing is phonetically close to the speaking.
Third, in Spanish, Toronto is stressed in the second "o," not in the last. It doesn't mean something else as you said it, just sounds funny ha ha.
Most important, and harder to explain, is that in Spanish we have two verbs that mean "to be," and they are "ser" and "estar." If you want to speak about permanent things, like being Canadian, you use "ser" (soy canadiense). If you mean something not permanent, like being tired, you use "estar" (estoy cansado).
Of course, there are nuances and little details in this general rule, like, when you speak about something/someone being alive or dead, you use "estar," the non-permanent verb.
Quite a philosophical statement in a grammatical characteristic.

i listened closely to the track, 0:06, and marked down what phonemes i heard and whether or not i could identify them. I counted something between 14 and 16 unique phonemes (counting potential phoneme clusters as separate sounds) and came up with a rough sketch of the sound*

(L) VV _ FP VV FVFF VV [N] (for example: woah, space is fine)
or
(L) VV _ FPL VV NFVFF VV [N] (for example: yo, strangest find)

*key: if the terms remain unclear, try looking them up

L=Liquid, a sound that "rolls" or is "fluid", like the /j/ in yeah or the /w/ in witty

F=fricative, a sound that nearly restricts airflow in the mouth, like the /s/ in stop or the /v/ in verily
P=Plosive, a sound that restricts airflow only to release it sharply- like the /t/ in terry or the /k/ in kite
V=Vowel, a non restrictive sound like the /æ/ in battle or the /e/ in best
N=Nasal, made by letting air pass through your nose as you speak- like the /m/ in miss or the /ŋ/ in sing

clusters are marked my surrounding the pair with dashes

uncertain or inferred sounds are marked with () and [] respectively
pauses will be marked with_underscores_

Oddly, I saw the woman's side profile face in the black and white image before the reveal, but I have my own personal theory of why. Growing up, we had kitchen and bathroom tiles with these abstract lines that were non-repeating, and I spent hours daydreaming while looking at them, trying to conjure images in my head. I noticed how frequently I had a tendency to imagine people, specifically faces, and sometimes scared myself if the images appeared menacing. I know this is n=1 but I'm pretty certain I'm not unique, and that it must be a very human condition to be searching for identifiable and relatable imagery, of something we can understand (i.e. a human face), when confronted with the abstract or unknown.
